WEBVTT

00:08.520 --> 00:12.620
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

00:28.740 --> 00:34.200
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

00:37.120 --> 00:38.580
And here are your hosts.

00:43.380 --> 00:44.580
This is David Crews.

00:44.880 --> 00:45.540
And Daryl Lane.

00:46.200 --> 00:50.700
If there's such a thing as a science fiction connoisseur, he would have to be a Jack Vance fan.

00:51.240 --> 00:55.620
Vance is a distinctive author who's been writing science fiction and fantasy since the 1940s.

00:55.880 --> 00:59.660
And even in a field like science fiction, Vance's imagination is remarkable.

00:59.660 --> 01:03.560
His depiction of alien worlds, for instance, impresses any reader.

01:04.200 --> 01:07.940
He has a powerful, subtle style with the colors and textures of his descriptions

01:07.940 --> 01:10.580
and his careful attention to the resources of language.

01:11.020 --> 01:14.840
He can make you believe you're on another planet, somehow involved in an alien culture.

01:15.620 --> 01:20.420
We might mention the Durdane trilogy or the four novels of the Tschai or Planet of Adventure series

01:20.420 --> 01:24.760
as examples of Vance's skill at creating alien environments and cultures.

01:25.520 --> 01:29.440
Vance always wanted to be a writer and he chose science fiction for the simplest of reasons.

01:30.900 --> 01:34.240
First, I had a toy with the idea of my life.

01:35.960 --> 01:42.200
And in order to find some way of making a living where I could travel, be my own boss,

01:42.660 --> 01:52.140
for 21 hours, and writing the way that suggests itself.

01:53.700 --> 02:03.840
And so I kind of, even when I was only 12 years old, I told myself I kind of liked to be a writer.

02:05.440 --> 02:10.200
Why I chose science fiction, I don't know, or fantasy, whatever you want to call it.

02:10.300 --> 02:13.080
I'd put out as a kid, I'd done a lot of reading.

02:14.560 --> 02:17.220
Well, I've done a lot of reading in everything as far as I could.

02:20.380 --> 02:31.400
But I think I probably more touched my, not influenced in a word, but influenced, I guess,

02:31.580 --> 02:42.000
you might say, by the fantasy and the so-called science fiction rather than by much anything else.

02:42.740 --> 02:46.880
As we've said, Vance started back in the 1940s in the Pulp magazines,

02:47.320 --> 02:50.860
and his early work lacks the polish and distinctive flair that he's known for.

02:51.800 --> 03:00.140
I was learning my trade. I just got started writing, not as real young as some guys did.

03:00.940 --> 03:02.580
In fact, I was doing lots of those things.

03:03.380 --> 03:06.560
And then I decided I was going to be a writer, and I started writing.

03:07.940 --> 03:11.560
I had all the talents for it, I guess, apparently.

03:12.440 --> 03:19.380
But I didn't have the knack or the practice, or whatever you want to call it, of putting the words together.

03:20.520 --> 03:26.860
And also, I was trying to write the wrong kind of story.

03:26.860 --> 03:30.560
Those days, the gadget story was very big.

03:32.420 --> 03:39.680
And I'd waste a lot of time trying to write gadget stories on scientific breakthroughs and things like that,

03:39.740 --> 03:47.340
which is essentially kind of a line-allic, I think.

03:49.100 --> 03:56.520
And it's a phase of the field which is mercifully going over the hill.

03:57.400 --> 04:01.780
I've got a very good scientific background, it's not that I don't know science, I do know it.

04:04.260 --> 04:08.360
I was going to be a physicist, actually, for a while.

04:08.360 --> 04:18.300
In the 40s and 50s, I was writing in the barrimony, collecting rejection slips.

04:19.400 --> 04:32.580
There was an apprentice period in which I was paid not very much for it, but, you know, Jack once in a while.

04:34.400 --> 04:40.000
But essentially, those 40 and 50 stories, they're not much good, they're not worth it.

04:41.220 --> 04:43.560
A gadget suit forget them.

04:44.900 --> 04:46.820
Vance's apprenticeship must have been well spent.

04:47.400 --> 04:50.320
The science fiction and fantasy he's been writing ever since is masterful.

04:50.780 --> 04:54.060
In 1963, he won the Hugo Award for the Dragon Masters.

04:54.660 --> 04:59.360
And in 1966, he won both the Nebula and Hugo Awards for The Last Castle.

04:59.360 --> 05:01.520
Tomorrow, more with Jack Vance.

