06:35.620 --> 06:39.900
Jack Vance has created a unique, vivid and fascinating body of science fiction and fantasy.

06:40.520 --> 06:45.640
He began his career in the pulp magazines of the 1940s, and he wrote the gadget stories that were popular then.

06:46.140 --> 06:50.900
But over the years, he's developed a deeper, more subtle and distinctive type of science fiction and fantasy.

06:50.900 --> 06:56.100
Yet the curious fact is that not many people, even science fiction readers, have heard of Jack Vance.

06:56.600 --> 06:58.240
We asked him why he thought that was so.

06:59.060 --> 07:12.100
I think another thing too that I've developed rather gradually in reach of my presence, whatever you want to call it,

07:12.100 --> 07:15.960
by kind of back way, inconspicuously.

07:17.280 --> 07:21.120
I remember Clark at the Home Courts in 2001,

07:23.060 --> 07:29.540
highlighting strange and estranged land or whatever children's books are, or through gambles.

07:33.980 --> 07:35.540
And it's a...

07:40.220 --> 07:46.540
I've never been associated with anything that has any other publicity attached to it.

07:47.240 --> 07:55.000
So I just seem to arrive on the scene, so it seems to me, if I were looking at my own career in this way,

07:55.000 --> 08:09.440
I would be kind of quietly from northeast somewhere rather than through having a movie or something or so.

08:10.700 --> 08:15.760
Lately, Vance has been writing three, four, and even five novel series set on alien planets.

08:16.180 --> 08:20.660
He's noted for his imaginative descriptions of alien settings and cultures more than anything else.

08:20.660 --> 08:27.620
The four books in the Chai series, or the Durdane trilogy, are good examples of stories set in convincingly alien environments.

08:28.340 --> 08:31.060
Vance is also recognized for the stories in the Dying Earth series.

08:31.680 --> 08:40.340
And don't forget, Vance has written excellent mystery fiction, even winning the Edgar Award from the Mystery Writers of America in 1960 for his book, The Man in the Cage.

08:41.380 --> 08:48.000
Even though some readers talk of a unique Vance style, Vance himself says he has no particular style or writing characteristics.

08:48.980 --> 08:55.980
I don't have any style. All I do is try to write whatever in the best possible way.

08:57.080 --> 09:06.280
Now, if you take the trouble to read some of my murder mysteries, you'll find that they're written in a different way.

09:07.520 --> 09:15.380
Everything you write, everything I write, everything anybody writes, the style or the way the words are put together

09:16.020 --> 09:23.920
is part of the mood of the story. It is part of the story itself. It's part of the complete product.

09:25.120 --> 09:40.300
Now, when you say, why did I, how did I evolve this, that implies that I have one style that I use for everything from this early Dying Earth thing

09:40.300 --> 09:52.460
up to one of the mystery stories with localum in the countryside out here called Fox Valley Murders.

09:53.140 --> 09:57.620
If you take the trouble to examine the way the words are put together, you'll find it totally different.

09:58.120 --> 10:06.580
Also like the bad rattle, which is a spence story, the way that the words go together, or different from the way the words go together,

10:06.580 --> 10:12.080
and say, oh, I don't know what. No, I don't have any style.

10:19.900 --> 10:27.640
Vance considers himself a storyteller or entertainer with no access to grind. He's reluctant to provide explanations or analyses of his work.

10:28.340 --> 10:33.620
When asked about a particular character or episode in one of his works, Vance has a characteristic reply.

10:34.840 --> 10:37.660
Well, I think everybody will have to answer that for themselves.

10:38.920 --> 10:45.180
Reading the science fiction of Jack Vance makes answering questions like that worthwhile. More with Jack Vance tomorrow.

