13:12.740 --> 13:16.680
But those were written all very, very early.

13:16.880 --> 13:19.540
They were written before I started selling.

13:21.880 --> 13:31.120
So they're just representative of kind of rather early, early stage.

13:32.540 --> 13:38.020
And then when I started writing the so-called gadget fiction or other stuff,

13:39.020 --> 13:43.560
I changed the style of the dying earth stuff.

13:43.720 --> 13:49.060
It wasn't at all suitable for writing the stuff I began selling.

13:50.440 --> 13:53.200
Stuff to stuff I was selling with it, because it wasn't.

13:53.660 --> 13:58.760
But at least the style of the dying earth would have been absolutely,

13:59.420 --> 14:04.760
uh, what sort of color was it?

14:05.200 --> 14:07.000
Wouldn't it fit it for you to give it a try?

14:18.720 --> 14:23.320
Many readers believe the style of the stories, which Vance calls flamboyant and highly colored,

14:23.560 --> 14:25.700
to be the most marvelous and vivid thing about them.

14:25.700 --> 14:31.080
It creates an exotic yet wistful atmosphere, somehow appropriate for a world on the edge of extinction.

14:31.640 --> 14:37.520
Tim Underwood is a friend of Vance's, and along with Chuck Miller, publishes Vance's work in specially made collector's editions.

14:38.340 --> 14:43.140
The Underwood Miller Publishing Company's first book was The Dying Earth. We asked Tim Underwood why.

14:44.140 --> 14:52.820
A lot of science fiction and fantasy, and sometimes the best of it, does not get published in hardcover editions.

14:52.820 --> 15:02.080
And The Dying Earth was the first book we did, and it was just a book that is essentially a, it's a classic.

15:02.900 --> 15:09.400
It was published in 1950 as a paperback, and it had never been in hardcover.

15:10.180 --> 15:16.960
And it's one of the outstanding books in the fantasy field, and 200 years from now people will be reading it.

15:16.960 --> 15:21.460
And it had never been in a durable hardcover edition, and so we put it in one.

15:28.960 --> 15:34.840
Vance didn't write any new Dying Earth material for 15 years after the book's original publication in 1950.

15:35.360 --> 15:39.340
We asked him if it was perhaps reader responses, which caused him to take it up again.

15:40.840 --> 15:45.060
No, it's been, I don't, I just, well, we're going to do some more stuff in there.

15:47.600 --> 15:53.560
In this, this character was, uh, swarming around in my head.

16:10.720 --> 16:17.520
The character swarming around in his head was Kugel, a picker-esque rogue who survives on the Dying Earth through his wits and his nimble fingers.

16:18.260 --> 16:23.100
The Kugel stories were collected in 1966 in a book entitled The Eyes of the Overworld.

16:23.940 --> 16:29.640
Since then, Vance has written other Kugel stories, and says he'll do more in the future, so the Dying Earth isn't dead yet.

