18:13.380 --> 18:19.140
I think Jack has accomplished some things with some of his works that have never been done before.

18:20.580 --> 18:31.340
Not only in terms of style, but in terms of feeling, he hearkens to a certain spirit, I think.

18:32.080 --> 18:41.480
A certain kind of person, a certain kind of spirit, is on his wavelengths and responds strongly to his work.

18:43.860 --> 18:49.820
The latter part of his work and the best of his work is extremely well crafted.

18:50.040 --> 18:56.600
He's a craftsman, very well written, and accomplishes a lot of really unusual things in a very quiet way.

18:58.120 --> 18:59.900
Vance's accomplishments have been impressive.

19:00.520 --> 19:03.980
His science fiction career spans almost 40 years and began back in the Pulp Era.

19:04.640 --> 19:07.280
He's won the major awards for his science fiction and fantasy writer.

19:07.280 --> 19:13.100
One is the Hugo Award, awarded by readers, and the other is the Nebula Award, given by other writers.

19:13.920 --> 19:22.800
Some of his best known work includes The Dying Earth Stories, which go all the way back to his beginnings as a writer in the 40s, and more recently, the five demon princes novels.

19:23.800 --> 19:27.200
Still, Vance hasn't received much recognition. We asked Underwood why.

19:28.420 --> 19:41.940
My feeling is that one responds strongly to Vance, one who feels much the same way about the world that he does.

19:42.260 --> 19:51.940
I think, why doesn't he though as popular as, say, John Lai Corre, who I think people respond to in the same way?

19:51.940 --> 20:03.660
Well, Vance is more of a rarefied taste, I think, is the kind of things that he feels are important.

20:04.100 --> 20:13.220
The strangeness in the world about us and the unusual qualities of life itself, those kind of considerations are not important to a lot of people.

20:14.620 --> 20:25.060
People who do feel these things strongly are going to like Vance's rights. They're going to enjoy reading. They're going to enjoy the world that he's created.

20:26.040 --> 20:32.160
He's not done a lot of the things that make other writers successful. Like, he's never stayed with one character.

20:33.060 --> 20:47.200
The way that, say, Lai Corre stayed with Smiley, or the way that someone writes a Doc Savage novel 15 times in a row, or whatever.

20:47.200 --> 20:57.120
He hasn't done that. And he hasn't had one hero that he's repeated for any great number of books.

20:57.300 --> 21:11.820
And he hasn't had one contemporary theme that appeals to people like the Battle of the Sexes or something like that. Those aren't Jack's themes.

21:11.820 --> 21:20.280
Jack's considerations and themes are enormously subtle and kind of a rarefied nature.

21:20.620 --> 21:28.080
Vance has always been reluctant to discuss his own work or to offer any insights into his themes or intentions. Underwood suggests a reason.

21:28.860 --> 21:38.580
Jack always says that he wants his work to span for and by itself. I think he just wants to be remembered for his work.

21:38.580 --> 21:46.820
He refuses to pick favorites among his work. I know he likes his Demon Prince series a lot for good reason.

21:47.820 --> 22:00.320
He likes The Palace of Love, which is the third in that series. He likes the Eyes of the Overworld, the sequenced stories of the fellow Cuckoo.

22:01.280 --> 22:08.200
And that's partly because Cuckoo is a rascal, and Vance and Soft is a bit of a rascal.

22:09.960 --> 22:18.540
